00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,600
Your mental scratchpad is tiny — that's why phone numbers feel hard to keep.

2
00:00:05,600 --> 00:00:12,800
Working memory can only hold about 7 items at once, a limit set by cognitive psychologist George Miller.

3
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:16,000
So, why do we struggle remembering longer numbers?

4
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:17,600
It’s all about chunking.

5
00:00:17,600 --> 00:00:22,400
Chunking means grouping information into manageable bits, like 555-1234 instead of 5551234.

6
00:00:22,400 --> 00:00:24,000
But did you know?

7
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:28,000
Cowan suggests we can hold even fewer when distractions hit.

8
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:34,000
Mastering chunking can boost your memory — whether for studying, phone numbers, or daily tasks.

